Three triggers on three different objects (keeping the one-trigger-per-object rule intact), each with a thin trigger file and the logic in a handler.

1. before insert — default values
apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert) {
    AccountTriggerHandler.applyDefaults(Trigger.new);
}
apex
public with sharing class AccountTriggerHandler {

    public static void applyDefaults(List<Account> newAccounts) {

        // Hierarchy custom setting — no SOQL, no governor cost
        AccountDefaults__c defaults = AccountDefaults__c.getInstance();
        String fallbackRating = (defaults != null && String.isNotBlank(defaults.Rating__c))
            ? defaults.Rating__c
            : 'Warm';

        for (Account acc : newAccounts) {

            if (String.isBlank(acc.Rating))       acc.Rating = fallbackRating;
            if (String.isBlank(acc.Type))         acc.Type = 'Prospect';
            if (acc.AnnualRevenue == null)        acc.AnnualRevenue = 0;
            if (String.isBlank(acc.BillingCountry)) acc.BillingCountry = 'India';

            // normalization belongs here too
            if (String.isNotBlank(acc.Name)) acc.Name = acc.Name.trim();
        }
    }
}

Note what's absent: no update statement. Assigning to Trigger.new in a before context is persisted by the save pipeline for free. Also note String.isBlank() rather than == null — it catches empty strings and whitespace, which is what you actually want for text fields coming from an integration or a data load.


