2. after insert — create child records
apex
trigger OpportunityTrigger on Opportunity (after insert) {
    OpportunityTriggerHandler.createKickoffTasks(Trigger.new);
}


public with sharing class OpportunityTriggerHandler {

    private static final Set<String> KICKOFF_STAGES =
        new Set<String>{ 'Prospecting', 'Qualification' };

    public static void createKickoffTasks(List<Opportunity> newOpps) {

        List<Task> toInsert = new List<Task>();

        for (Opportunity opp : newOpps) {

            if (!KICKOFF_STAGES.contains(opp.StageName)) continue;

            toInsert.add(new Task(
                WhatId       = opp.Id,          // ← the reason this is `after`
                OwnerId      = opp.OwnerId,
                Subject      = 'Kickoff call: ' + opp.Name,
                ActivityDate = Date.today().addDays(3),
                Priority     = 'High',
                Status       = 'Not Started'
            ));
        }

        if (toInsert.isEmpty()) return;

        // allOrNone = false: one bad child doesn't roll back all 200 parents
        List<Database.SaveResult> results = Database.insert(toInsert, false);

        for (Integer i = 0; i < results.size(); i++) {
            if (!results[i].isSuccess()) {
                System.debug(LoggingLevel.ERROR,
                    'Kickoff task failed for ' + toInsert[i].WhatId + ': ' +
                    results[i].getErrors()[0].getMessage());
            }
        }
    }
}

Three things worth flagging:

One insert for the whole batch. Collect into a list, DML once outside the loop. insert inside the for loop is the single most common trigger bug and it dies at 151 records.
Database.insert(list, false) vs plain insert. Plain insert is all-or-nothing — one failure throws and rolls back the entire transaction including the Opportunities. Partial-success mode lets the good ones through and hands you SaveResult objects to inspect. Choose deliberately; for side-effect records like activity logs, partial success is almost always right.
WhatId needs the Id, which is exactly why this can't be a before insert.

