3. before update — validation
apex
trigger CaseTrigger on Case (before update) {
    CaseTriggerHandler.validateClosure(Trigger.new, Trigger.oldMap);
}

public with sharing class CaseTriggerHandler {

    public static void validateClosure(List<Case> newCases, Map<Id, Case> oldMap) {

        // Phase 1: find records that are *transitioning* into Closed
        Set<Id> closingIds = new Set<Id>();

        for (Case c : newCases) {
            Case oldCase = oldMap.get(c.Id);
            if (c.Status == 'Closed' && oldCase.Status != 'Closed') {
                closingIds.add(c.Id);
            }
        }

        if (closingIds.isEmpty()) return;   // cheap exit — most saves won't qualify

        // Phase 2: one aggregate query for all of them
        Map<Id, Integer> openTasksByCase = new Map<Id, Integer>();
        for (AggregateResult ar : [
            SELECT WhatId wid, COUNT(Id) cnt
            FROM Task
            WHERE WhatId IN :closingIds
              AND IsClosed = false
            GROUP BY WhatId
        ]) {
            openTasksByCase.put((Id) ar.get('wid'), (Integer) ar.get('cnt'));
        }

        // Phase 3: apply errors
        for (Case c : newCases) {

            if (!closingIds.contains(c.Id)) continue;

            if (String.isBlank(c.Description)) {
                c.Description.addError('A resolution summary is required before closing.');
            }

            if (String.isBlank(c.Reason)) {
                c.Reason.addError('Select a case reason before closing.');
            }

            Integer openCount = openTasksByCase.get(c.Id);
            if (openCount != null && openCount > 0) {
                c.addError('Cannot close: ' + openCount + ' open task(s) remain.');
            }
        }
    }
}

The collect → query → apply shape is the standard bulkified structure, and it's the same instinct as batching an N+1 into a single IN query. Note the early return — skipping the SOQL entirely when nothing qualifies matters when the trigger fires on every save.

On addError specifically:

record.addError(msg) → error banner at the top of the page. record.Field.addError(msg) → error rendered inline next to that field, but only if the field is on the page layout; otherwise the user sees nothing and just wonders why the save failed. Prefer record-level when you're unsure.
It doesn't throw. Execution continues, so you can accumulate errors across several fields and several records in one pass — which is why you can flag record 7 and record 12 independently in the same batch.
The message is HTML-escaped by default. addError(msg, false) disables escaping if you need markup, which also means you own the injection risk — same reasoning as the dynamic SOQL escaping you covered earlier.
In a bulk DML, a single addError on one record fails only that record when the caller used Database.update(list, false); with plain update the whole batch rolls back.



