Consolidating

If all three patterns lived on one object, you'd have a single trigger routing by context rather than three files:

apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, after insert, before update) {

    switch on Trigger.operationType {
        when BEFORE_INSERT { AccountTriggerHandler.applyDefaults(Trigger.new); }
        when AFTER_INSERT  { AccountTriggerHandler.createChildren(Trigger.new); }
        when BEFORE_UPDATE { AccountTriggerHandler.validate(Trigger.new, Trigger.oldMap); }
    }
}

Trigger.operationType with switch on is cleaner than nested isBefore/isInsert booleans, and the compiler catches typos in the enum values.

For test coverage, each of these needs at least a bulk test (201 records, proving no governor blowup), a positive case, and — for the validation one — a negative case wrapping the DML in try/catch and asserting on DmlException.getDmlMessage(0). That's probably the natural next stop in the series, along with the recursion guard pattern.

